{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"83287d31-8f70-478f-bcdc-926e462462d9","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — re-installs the workloads you already have **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** After an SDK update, the workloads need *newer* versions, not a reinstall of the old ones. Run:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after that, try `dotnet workload install maui` to ensure the MAUI workload is fully present.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"270d4eb9-d92c-4c90-801e-629f131d12d9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":263,"requestId":"DBD0:19AB05:8449F:A49FD:69F549EF"},"id":"5c7ff1d5-be2e-4bc1-a05b-d79d7b62a8fc","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:48:54.855Z","parentId":"5232dd0d-b34b-4375-8716-e153fec18b94"}
